            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18131027-82-person863">
                  WILLIAM 
                  GREEN
               <interp inst="t18131027-82-person863" type="surname" value="GREEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18131027-82-person863" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18131027-82-person863" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18131027-82-viclabel483" type="occupation">wheelwright</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18131027-82-victim862 t18131027-82-viclabel483"></join>; I live in <rs id="t18131027-82-viclabel484" type="occupation">White Horse-street, Commercial-road</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18131027-82-victim862 t18131027-82-viclabel484"></join>. From information I watched the prisoner, when he went from work of a night; I detected him with a bottle of turpentine, and a stone jar of white-lead; I took him with the property before a magistrate.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18131027-82-person864">
                  RICHARD 
                  RICHARDS
               <interp inst="t18131027-82-person864" type="surname" value="RICHARDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18131027-82-person864" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18131027-82-person864" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 7th of October, I saw an empty bottle and an empty jar under the bench, where the paint stood, and almost instantly I missed them; I told Mr. Green. He unlocked the prisoner's cupboard; the bottle was there full of turpentine, and the jar full of white lead; he desired me to keep an eye on the prisoner. In the evening, about half past six, I heard the prisoner unlock the cupboard; he then went out; after he was gone, I looked in the cupboard; the bottle of turpentine was gone, and the jar of white-lead also. Mr. Green pursued him, and took him, and brought him back<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181310270055"></xptr>with the property on him; he said he hoped Mr. Green would forgive him.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18131027-82-verdict485" type="verdictDescription">
